03987nam a22004935i 9780822391890DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223918907 a10.1515/97808223918902doi  a(DE-B1597)553057  a(OCoLC)846485332  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aFaudree, Paja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSinging for the Dead :bThe Politics of Indigenous Revival in Mexico /cPaja Faudree. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b23 photographs, 4 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Orthographic and Linguistic Conventions -- tIntroduction: Leaving the Pueblo -- t1. From Revolution to Renaissance A Political Geography and History of “Deep Mexico” -- t2. Revival in the “Land of the Magic Mushroom” A Recent History of Ethnic Relations in the Sierra Mazateca -- t3. Singing for the Spirits The Annual Day of the Dead Song Contest -- t4. Scenes from a Nativist Reformation The Mazatec Indigenous Church -- t5. Meeting at the Family Crypt Social Fault Lines and the Fragility of Community -- t6. Seeing Double Indigenous Authors, Readers, and the Paradox of Revival -- tConclusion: Singing for the Dead and the Living Revival, Indigenous Publics, and the National Afterlife -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSinging for the Dead chronicles ethnic revival in Oaxaca, Mexico, where new forms of singing and writing in the local Mazatec indigenous language are producing powerful, transformative political effects. Paja Faudree argues for the inclusion of singing as a necessary component in the polarized debates about indigenous orality and literacy, and she considers how the coupling of literacy and song has allowed people from the region to create texts of enduring social resonance. She examines how local young people are learning to read and write in Mazatec as a result of the region's new Day of the Dead song contest. Faudree also studies how tourist interest in local psychedelic mushrooms has led to their commodification, producing both opportunities and challenges for songwriters and others who represent Mazatec culture. She situates these revival movements within the contexts of Mexico and Latin America, as well as the broad, hemisphere-wide movement to create indigenous literatures. Singing for the Dead provides a new way to think about the politics of ethnicity, the success of social movements, and the limits of national belonging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391890zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391890423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822391890/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles